      },
      "date": "2015-04-13 20:09:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nJinshan -\n\nI think not, for the same reason we don't take it (any more) in the non-direct IO path. It allows parallelism between multiple threads doing direct IO.\n\nIs there some other reason you think we should take the mutex?\n\nAlso, if the old comment removed by LU-1669 was right, we also need to protect it from the buffered IO path, and since that path doesn't take the mutex any more, that means the range lock:\n/* 0. Need locking between buffered and direct access. and race with\n\n    size changing by concurrent truncates and writes.\n    1. Need inode mutex to operate transient pages.\n    */\n    if (rw == READ)\n    mutex_lock(&inode->i_mutex);",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
